<paragraph blockId="7.[151,918,1556,1615]" box="[151,235,1590,1615]" pageId="7">
(
<figureCitation box="[159,227,1590,1615]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1662,2011]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="8" pageId="7">
The specimens found in the littoral zone of Moyangjiang River (
<figureCitation box="[878,967,1662,1687]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[980,1049,1662,1687]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[147,231,671,693]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1. Sampling locality information." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF3D6635FFDCFFC0FF6C748B365FFD1B" pageId="7" tableUuid="DF3D6635FFDCFFC0FF6C748B365FFD1B">Tab. 1</tableCitation>
), and in another three localities in Changde City, Hunan Province, on 
<date box="[578,808,1698,1723]" pageId="7" value="2017-09-16">16 September 2017</date>
(
<figureCitation box="[830,902,1698,1723]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
B–4E), largely conform to the description of 
<taxonomicName authority="Novotna-Dvorakova, 1963" authorityName="Novotna-Dvorakova" authorityYear="1963" box="[151,835,1734,1759]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="variety" species="caudatus" variety="indica">
<emphasis box="[151,390,1734,1759]" italics="true" pageId="7">Brachionus caudatus</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[450,520,1734,1759]" italics="true" pageId="7">indica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Novotna-Dvorakova, M." box="[530,835,1734,1759]" pageId="7" pagination="170 - 177" refId="ref5309" refString="Novotna-Dvorakova, M. (1963) Rotatorien des Flusses Yamuna (Indien). Vestnik Ceskoslovenske spolecnosti zoologicke, 27 (3), 170 - 177, pls. 1 - 2." type="journal article" year="1963">Novotná-Dvořáková, 1963</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and only differ in minor aspects. The antero-lateral dorsal spines are almost as long as the median spines in specimens from Moyangjiang River and Changde, while they are longer than the median ones in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Novotna-Dvorakova" authorityYear="1963" box="[595,851,1806,1831]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="variety" species="caudatus" variety="indica">
<emphasis box="[595,727,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="7">B. caudatus</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[781,851,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="7">indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, the ventral median sulcus of the anterior aperture is much deeper in specimens from Moyangjiang River (
<figureCitation box="[891,980,1842,1867]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
) if compared to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Novotna-Dvorakova" authorityYear="1963" box="[1173,1436,1842,1867]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="variety" species="caudatus" variety="indica">
<emphasis box="[1173,1307,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="7">B. caudatus</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1366,1436,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="7">indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and specimens from Changde City (
<figureCitation box="[553,641,1878,1903]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Our specimens also show a high similarity with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[1199,1436,1878,1903]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[1199,1436,1878,1903]" italics="true" pageId="7">Brachionus caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[174,300,1914,1939]" italics="true" pageId="7">majusculus</emphasis>
Ahlstrom, 1940 from Florida, from which they differ by ventrally directed posterior spines (
<figureCitation box="[1336,1424,1914,1939]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionTargetBox="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" pageId="7">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
). These are inserted in the same plane as the body axis in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[800,933,1950,1975]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[800,933,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="7">B. caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[967,1092,1950,1975]" italics="true" pageId="7">majusculus</emphasis>
. Another similar infraspecific taxon that has been described within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[606,707,1986,2011]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[606,707,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="7">caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-complex and that requires attention here is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[1199,1436,1986,2011]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="7" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[1199,1436,1986,2011]" italics="true" pageId="7">Brachionus caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[179,268,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="8">apsteini</emphasis>
Fadeev, 1925. As in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Novotna-Dvorakova" authorityYear="1963" box="[529,652,151,176]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="8" phylum="Rotifera" rank="variety" species="caudatus" variety="indica">
var. 
<emphasis box="[582,652,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="8">indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, posterior spines arise at an angle ventrally in f. 
<emphasis box="[1246,1335,153,176]" italics="true" pageId="8">apsteini</emphasis>
, but are relatively shorter. Previous records of a variant of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[743,879,188,213]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="8" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[743,879,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="8">B. caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, sub 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[946,1082,188,213]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="8" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[946,1082,188,213]" italics="true" pageId="8">B. caudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
f. 
<emphasis box="[1120,1209,189,212]" italics="true" pageId="8">apsteini</emphasis>
Fadeev, 1925, as a common taxon in the Southwestern Islands of 
<collectingCountry box="[667,734,224,247]" name="Japan" pageId="8">Japan</collectingCountry>
, show a striking resemblance to our 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Novotna-Dvorakova" authorityYear="1963" box="[1138,1429,223,248]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="8" phylum="Rotifera" rank="variety" species="caudatus" variety="indica">
<emphasis box="[1138,1162,225,248]" italics="true" pageId="8">B.</emphasis>
cf. 
<emphasis box="[1204,1305,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="8">caudatus</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1359,1429,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="8">indica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and most likely concern the same taxon (
<bibRefCitation author="Sudzuki, M." box="[617,785,260,285]" pageId="8" pagination="29 - 70" refId="ref5554" refString="Sudzuki, M. (1992) Seasonal and local occurrences of the Rotifera in southwestern islands of Japan. Japanese Society of Systematic Zoology, 46, 29 - 70, pls. 1 - 32." type="journal article" year="1992">Sudzuki, 1992</bibRefCitation>
: Plate XII: 
<figureCitation box="[916,1018,260,285]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 2" captionStart-1="FIGURE 3" captionStart-2="FIGURE 4" captionStart-3="FIGURE 5" captionStart-4="FIGURE 6" captionStart-5="FIGURE 7" captionStartId-0="5.[151,250,1935,1957]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,250,1955,1977]" captionStartId-2="8.[151,250,1387,1409]" captionStartId-3="9.[151,250,1798,1820]" captionStartId-4="10.[151,250,1375,1397]" captionStartId-5="11.[151,250,1125,1147]" captionTargetBox-0="[218,1337,202,1908]" captionTargetBox-1="[213,1373,1060,1931]" captionTargetBox-2="[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetBox-3="[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetBox-4="[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetBox-5="[157,1411,195,1103]" captionTargetId-0="figure@5.[217,1351,195,1909]" captionTargetId-1="figure@6.[213,1373,1060,1931]" captionTargetId-2="figure@8.[157,1441,451,1347]" captionTargetId-3="figure@9.[150,1436,863,1755]" captionTargetId-4="figure@10.[302,1289,193,1343]" captionTargetId-5="figure@11.[157,1412,195,1104]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionTargetPageId-2="8" captionTargetPageId-3="9" captionTargetPageId-4="10" captionTargetPageId-5="11" captionText-0="FIGURE 2. Lecane zhanjiangensis sp. nov. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, ventral view. C. Not well-contracted head with spines, dorsal view. D. Light microscope photograph of Holotype, ventral view. E. Habitus, dorsal view, U.S. specimen modified from Turner (1996). Arrows indicate the spines on the outside of head. Scale bars: A–E: 50 µm." captionText-1="FIGURE 3. Lecane zhanjiangensis sp. nov., scanning electron microscope photographs of trophi. A. Complete set, ventral view. B. Complete set, dorsal view. C. Unci and rami, ventral view. D. Unci and rami, dorsal view. Scale bar: 5 µm." captionText-2="FIGURE 4. Light microscope photograph of Brachionus cf. caudatus var. indica. A, C. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Anterior lorica aperture, ventral view. D. Foot opening, ventral view. E. Habitus, lateral view. Scale bar: 50 µm. Specimen in Fig. 4A from Moyangjiang River, Yangjiang, Guangdong Province and specimens in Fig. 4A–4E from Changde, Hunan Province." captionText-3="FIGURE 5. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura libera. A. Habitus, dorsal view. B. Habitus, lateral view. C–E. Anterior part of body, lateral view. F. Peduncle (attachment stalk) and gelatinous tube. Arrows show the excreting anus. Scale bar: A–F: 50 µm." captionText-4="FIGURE 6. Ptygura libera, scanning electron microscope photographs of trophi. A. Complete set, frontal view. B. Complete set, caudal view. C. Unci and rami, frontal view. D. Unci and rami, caudal view. Scale bar: A–D: 2 µm." captionText-5="FIGURE 7. Light microscope photograph of Ptygura thalenoiensis. A. Habitus, lateral view. B. Peduncle and gelatinous tube, lateral view. C. Corona, lateral view. D, F. Dorsal hooks and cylindrical projection, lateral view. E. Dorsal hooks and cylindrical projection, dorsal view. G, H. Corona, frontal view. Arrows show the cylindrical projection with elongate cilia in Fig. 5C and the dorsal hooks and cylindrical projection in Fig. 5D–5F. Scale bar: A–C, E–H: 50 µm; D: 10 µm." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/2673287/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/2673289/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/2673291/files/figure.png" httpUri-3="https://zenodo.org/record/2673293/files/figure.png" httpUri-4="https://zenodo.org/record/2673295/files/figure.png" httpUri-5="https://zenodo.org/record/2673297/files/figure.png" pageId="8">Figs 2–7</figureCitation>
). Further specimen material needs to be examined by also including molecular methods to determine the taxonomic status of these supposedly infraspecific taxa within the highly variable morphospecies 
<taxonomicName authority="Barrois &amp; Daday, 1894" authorityName="Barrois &amp; Daday" authorityYear="1894" box="[822,1224,332,357]" class="Eurotatoria" family="Brachionidae" genus="Brachionus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ploima" pageId="8" phylum="Rotifera" rank="species" species="caudatus">
<emphasis box="[822,954,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="8">B. caudatus</emphasis>
Barrois &amp; Daday, 1894
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
